    explanation: "Severe symptomatic mitral stenosis in pregnancy is associated with significant maternal and fetal morbidity. This patient has haemodynamically severe MS (MVA <1.0 cm²) with symptoms at 28 weeks. In patients with favourable valve anatomy (no significant subvalvular disease, pliable leaflets, no MR) who remain symptomatic despite medical therapy, percutaneous mitral balloon commissurotomy (PMBC) is the procedure of choice during pregnancy — it can be performed from the second trimester with appropriate shielding to reduce fetal radiation exposure. Rate control with beta-blockers (metoprolol preferred — safe in pregnancy) and anticoagulation with LMWH (for AF) should be optimised, but definitive intervention is needed given MVA 0.9 cm². Open valve surgery carries high fetal mortality (15–30%) and is reserved for cases where PMBC fails. Caesarean section alone does not address the valvular pathology.",
