    stem: "A 35-year-old woman 6 weeks postpartum presents with a 2-week history of progressive dyspnoea, orthopnoea, and bilateral leg swelling. She had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery at term. She has no prior cardiac history. On examination, her JVP is elevated, she has bibasal crackles, an S3 gallop, and 2+ pitting oedema. Her ECG shows sinus tachycardia with non-specific T-wave changes. Echocardiogram reveals global LV dysfunction with an ejection fraction of 25%. What is the most likely diagnosis and the most important medication to AVOID in her management?",
