    explanation: "This patient has symptomatic decompensated heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) with signs of fluid overload (elevated JVP, bibasal crackles, peripheral oedema). The immediate priority is decongestion with a loop diuretic (furosemide) to relieve symptoms. Spironolactone (a mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist/MRA) should also be added as it has proven mortality benefit in HFrEF with LVEF <35% (RALES trial) and is recommended by Australian guidelines for NYHA class II-IV patients already on ACE inhibitor and beta-blocker. Increasing beta-blocker dose is contraindicated in acute decompensation. While sacubitril/valsartan is recommended for stable HFrEF patients on optimised therapy, it is not the immediate priority in an acutely decompensated patient, and the ACE inhibitor must be ceased 36 hours before initiation. Digoxin has a limited role and is not a priority addition here.",
