    explanation: "Distinguishing athlete's heart from hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is a critical clinical challenge. Features favouring physiological adaptation (athlete's heart) include: septal thickness typically 12–16 mm (overlap zone with HCM), dilated LV cavity (>55 mm in males), symmetric hypertrophy, normal/supranormal diastolic function, excellent exercise tolerance (high VO2 max), ECG changes attributable to training, and no family history of HCM or sudden cardiac death. In HCM, the LV cavity is typically small or normal (<45 mm), hypertrophy is often asymmetric, diastolic dysfunction may be present, and VO2 max is reduced. This patient's dilated LV cavity of 58 mm, high VO2 max, and absence of family history strongly favour athlete's heart. Deconditioning echocardiography (repeat after 3 months of detraining) showing regression of hypertrophy would confirm the diagnosis.",
