    stem: "A 35-year-old woman is referred with a 3-month history of progressive dyspnoea, orthopnoea, and bilateral ankle oedema. She gave birth to her first child 4 months ago and had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery. Prior to pregnancy she was entirely well. Echocardiography shows dilated left ventricle (LV end-diastolic diameter 65 mm) with global hypokinesia and an ejection fraction of 28%. There is no family history of cardiac disease. What is the most likely diagnosis?",
