    explanation: "This patient has severe rheumatic mitral stenosis (MVA 1.2 cm², symptomatic) with favourable valve morphology — pliable leaflets, minimal calcification, and commissural fusion — making her an ideal candidate for percutaneous mitral balloon commissurotomy (PMBC), also known as percutaneous mitral valvotomy. PMBC is the procedure of choice in young patients with rheumatic MS and favourable anatomy (Wilkins score ≤8), as it is less invasive than surgery, has excellent short and long-term outcomes, and avoids the need for cardiopulmonary bypass. The presence of AF in a young woman with MS is an additional indication for intervention given the risk of thromboembolic events. Mitral valve replacement is reserved for patients with unfavourable anatomy (heavy calcification, severe subvalvar disease), significant MR, or failed PMBC. Annuloplasty is used for regurgitation, not stenosis. Medical management alone is insufficient in symptomatic severe MS.",
