    explanation: "This patient has critical limb ischaemia (CLI), defined by rest pain, tissue loss (ischaemic ulcer), ABI <0.4, and toe pressure <30 mmHg. CLI represents the most severe stage of PAD (Rutherford category 4-6) and carries a high risk of limb loss and mortality without urgent revascularisation. Urgent vascular surgical referral is mandatory for prompt assessment and revascularisation — either endovascular (angioplasty/stenting) or surgical bypass depending on anatomy. The goal is limb salvage and prevention of major amputation. Exercise rehabilitation is contraindicated in CLI as it worsens ischaemia. Cilostazol is contraindicated in patients with heart failure and is only indicated for claudication, not CLI. Primary amputation without attempting revascularisation is inappropriate unless the limb is clearly non-viable or the patient is not a surgical candidate. Wound care alone without improving blood flow will not heal an ischaemic ulcer.",
