    explanation: "The management of isolated distal (calf) DVT is controversial but per current Australian guidelines (ASTH and Therapeutic Guidelines), for low-risk patients with no symptoms of PE, no high-risk features (malignancy, recurrence, severe symptoms), and a clearly provoked distal DVT, a strategy of serial imaging with repeat ultrasound in 1-2 weeks is acceptable as an alternative to immediate anticoagulation. Approximately 25% of untreated distal DVTs extend proximally, and anticoagulation is initiated if extension occurs. This approach avoids unnecessary bleeding risks from anticoagulation in a low-risk patient. If the patient had high-risk features (bilateral, symptomatic, prior VTE, active cancer), full anticoagulation would be preferred. A 3-month course of a DOAC is a reasonable alternative approach, particularly if the patient would find follow-up imaging inconvenient. Aspirin is not therapeutic for DVT. Thrombolysis is reserved for massive/life-threatening PE or massive iliofemoral DVT with limb threat.",
