    explanation: "This is a hypertensive emergency with end-organ damage (hypertensive encephalopathy, papilloedema, acute kidney injury, LVH with haematuria and proteinuria). Management requires controlled parenteral antihypertensive therapy with the goal of reducing mean arterial pressure by no more than 20–25% in the first hour to avoid ischaemic complications from autoregulatory failure. IV labetalol (or nicardipine) is a preferred agent due to its predictable titratability and combined alpha/beta-blocking effect. Sublingual immediate-release nifedipine is dangerous and contraindicated — it causes precipitous and uncontrolled BP drops leading to stroke and MI. Sodium nitroprusside reduces BP too rapidly and carries cyanide toxicity risk with prolonged use. Oral agents do not provide adequate control speed or predictability in this emergency setting. The patient requires ICU admission.",
