    explanation: "The combination of delta waves, short PR interval, wide complex tachycardia during exertion, and family history of sudden cardiac death is classic for Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome. In WPW, an accessory pathway (bundle of Kent) bypasses the AV node, and if AF develops, rapid antegrade conduction via the accessory pathway can lead to pre-excited AF with very high ventricular rates and risk of degeneration to ventricular fibrillation. This is a medical emergency, and AV nodal blocking agents (digoxin, verapamil, adenosine) are contraindicated as they can accelerate accessory pathway conduction. DC cardioversion is appropriate for haemodynamically compromised patients. Definitive treatment is radiofrequency catheter ablation of the accessory pathway. Brugada and long QT syndromes do not exhibit delta waves.",
